<p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6c757d; margin-top: 0.5rem; text-align: center;">
  Video: An American traveler tests how safe China really is.
</p>
    
    <p>I arrived in China with a list of warnings from back home:<br />
    “Never leave your bag unattended.”<br />
    “Keep your phone in your front pocket.”<br />
    “Don’t trust strangers too easily.”</p>

    <p>So on my first morning in Shanghai, when I walked into a Starbucks and saw laptops, phones, and designer bags sitting alone on tables while their owners queued for coffee, I froze.<br />
    Where are the security guards?<br />
    Why isn’t anyone watching their stuff?</p>

    <p>My friend Lucy, who had lived in China for two years, just laughed.<br />
    “People don’t steal here like they do in London,” she said. “Just put your bag down, go order, and come back. Nothing will happen.”</p>

    <p>I didn’t believe her.<br />
    So I did a little experiment. I left my phone on the table, my open backpack beside it, and walked to the counter. My heart pounded. I kept glancing over my shoulder.</p>

    <p>By the time I got my latte, everything was still there. I tried again the next day, left my laptop this time. Same result.</p>

    <p>It felt unreal. In London, that laptop would have been gone in sixty seconds.</p>

    <p>This "trust as default" thing started to sink in. I stopped clutching my bag like a nervous cat. I began to enjoy the freedom of not having to guard every little thing.</p>

    <p>And then, in Chengdu, the real test came.</p>

    <p>I was at a popular scenic spot, taking photos of the old teahouses. It was crowded. I got distracted by a street performer, put my backpack down on a bench to get a better angle, and walked off. Fifteen minutes later, I realised my bag was gone.</p>

    <p>Inside: my passport, my wallet, my power bank, and worst of all, a small hard drive with all my travel photos and journal drafts.</p>

    <p>My heart sank. For a moment, the old fear crept back. <em>This is it. This is what they warned me about.</em></p>

    <p>I rushed to a nearby police booth, barely able to explain myself. The officer spoke a little English. He asked calmly: "Where? When? What colour bag?"</p>

    <p>He pulled up a tablet and tapped a few times. Within minutes, he was scrolling through security footage from a camera on a lamppost. There I was, putting the bag down. Then me walking away. Then a minute later, an elderly woman picking it up and walking towards a ticket office.</p>

    <p>"Don't worry," the officer said. "She probably turned it in. That's what people do here."</p>

    <p>We walked to the ticket office. And sure enough, there was my backpack, sitting behind the counter. A young woman handed it to me. "We were waiting for you," she said. "We saw you leave it. We knew you'd come back."</p>

    <p>Everything was inside. Nothing missing. Not even the loose change.</p>

    <p>I cried a little. Not from relief, from something bigger. In my country, if you lose your bag in a crowded tourist spot, it's gone. Forever. The police might file a report, but they wouldn't sit with you and scroll through cameras within minutes. And a stranger? Most would not go out of their way to turn it in.</p>

    <p>That night, I sat in a quiet hostel room and thought about what I'd learned.<br />
    China isn't just a place where people leave laptops in cafes. It's a place where even when things go wrong, the system and the people work together to make it right.</p>

    <p>The cameras I'd heard about? They're not watching you. They're watching out for you.<br />
    The trust I'd tested in Starbucks? It's not blind. It's backed by something real.</p>

    <p>I wrote in my journal that night:<br />
    "Trust is the default here. And when that fails, the village still has your back."</p>

    <p>That's the China I now carry with me, not just the pandas and the skyscrapers, but the quiet, solid feeling that you're never really alone.</p>


